Schedulaa vs QuickBooks Payroll

Real Pricing and Operations Comparison for 20-Employee Teams

QuickBooks Payroll vs Schedulaa is one of the most common questions we hear from service businesses with 10–50 employees.

This guide walks through:
- the real monthly cost of QuickBooks Payroll for a 20-employee team
- what Schedulaa includes at the same headcount
- the operational gaps that cause most payroll errors
- when Schedulaa is a better QuickBooks Payroll alternative for service teams

1. QuickBooks Payroll Pricing (Real Cost for 20 Employees)

QuickBooks sells payroll only. Pricing is a base fee plus per-employee fee, and discounts typically apply for the first six months only.

QuickBooks Online Payroll Plans
Core
- Base: $25/mo promo (then $50/mo)
- Per employee: $4/mo
- 20 employees: 20 × $4 = $80/mo
- Total: $25 + $80 = $105/mo (promo months ~$86.25)

Premium
- Base: $55/mo promo (then $80/mo)
- Per employee: $8/mo
- 20 employees: 20 × $8 = $160/mo
- Total: $55 + $160 = $215/mo (promo months ~$173.75)

Elite
- Base: $80/mo promo (then $125/mo)
- Per employee: $15/mo
- 20 employees: 20 × $15 = $300/mo
- Total: $80 + $300 = $380/mo (promo months ~$320)

After the promotion ends, a 20-employee company pays $105, $215, or $380 per month for payroll only. There is no scheduling, no break enforcement, no PTO accrual logic, no multi-step approvals, and no unified audit trail across shifts. All of that must be handled manually or with additional third-party tools.

