4. True Cost Comparison (20 Employees)

QuickBooks Payroll Premium → $215/mo for payroll only. Realistic stack once you add scheduling ($40–$80), time tracking ($30–$60), and PTO tools often lands between $300–$450/mo.

Schedulaa Business → $219.99/mo all-in for scheduling, break management, time tracking, PTO, payroll, compliance exports, websites, checkout, and accounting exports.

5. Feature & Workflow Difference
QuickBooks Payroll focuses on running payroll once data is already clean. No native scheduling, break enforcement, clock-ins, PTO accruals, shift swaps, or multi-location workflows.

Schedulaa fixes operations before payroll, tying booking, scheduling, breaks, and time tracking together. Every shift, break, PTO request, and timesheet flows into payroll automatically, generating W-2, T4, ROE, and summarizing payroll data for QuickBooks or Xero.

6. Who Should Use Schedulaa Instead of QuickBooks Payroll Alone?
Schedulaa is a better fit if you run a service team with 3–50 employees, need scheduling + payroll in one system, are tired of manual PTO and fragmented apps, want clean audit trails, need US + Canada payroll, or still want your accountant to use QuickBooks/Xero without day-to-day chaos.

7. Summary: Schedulaa vs QuickBooks Payroll
- QuickBooks pricing punishes growth with per-employee fees and extra tools.
- Schedulaa pricing is predictable: base tier + $9 per extra staff.
- QuickBooks solves payroll. Schedulaa solves operations.
- QuickBooks bolts into your workflow. Schedulaa is the workflow.
- QuickBooks requires accountants to reconcile multiple tools. Schedulaa captures everything in one system.

For growing service businesses, Schedulaa is both a complete QuickBooks Payroll alternative and a cleaner way to feed accurate data back into QuickBooks or Xero.
